<font color="#FF0000">GUILT AND AMERICAN PRIDE!</font><br>
<tt>Sun Jul 27 13:27:48 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
      <br>
When I was a child, I saw my older brother in his sharp dressy military uniform. He was in the Army, but I guess that was alright since he still looked sharp with all those colorful ribbons across his chest, the patches on his shoulders, stars, and bells and all sorts of shiny things that glittered, and devices that dangled. He looked like the walking 4th of July and I was so very proud of him. I wished then and perhaps even prayed that when I grew up, that there would be war going on. I wanted to fight for my country, serve others, and get to wear those shinny medals and ribbons upon my chest.<br><br>
When I turned 18, I joined the Marine Corps. I volunteered for duty. Marines during that time were not drafted. I have never forgotten the first time I opened up in battle. It happened just a couple of weeks after the 4th of July 30 years ago, on Hill St. Peter, July 22, 1967.<br><br>
Three days after Bro and Stroker had been killed, we set up in the same location. Just to the right of the spot where they had been ambushed. I set up the M60 machine gun on a dirt grave mound near the tree line, while the rest of the platoon was set up to our left.  We had set up in an &quot;L&quot; shaped ambush. The remains of 1st squad and our gun team made up the shorter end of the &quot;L&quot; shaped ambush we were facing toward the village while the lieutenant, the CP and the other two squads were facing North, covering the thicker section of the dense jungle.  Heavy underbrush and tropical trees surrounded us.  <br><br>
I set up the gun facing down a trail that was overgrown with weeds and tall elephant grass. The trail also served as a rice paddy dike that led toward the village. We could tell that the trail was used, but not often.  The rice paddies in between were neglected and overgrown with bushes, bamboo shoots and six foot tall elephant grass. John and Jones were covering the trail while I covered their backs. My back was toward the trail. <br>
The M60 machine gun is an effective, reliable and accurate weapon.  It weighs only 23 pounds, slightly more with the 100 round ammo pouch attached. It has two attached front retractable bipod legs and with them extended, one can easily pick off an enemy 1,000 yards away. When it rests on its tripod, its effective range is up to 1,900 yards away. The effective rate of fire is from 200 to 550 rounds per minute. However, one can shoot 750 rounds a minute if needed in a firefight, but at that rate of fire, the barrel of the gun begins to melt. I would melt three barrels in combat during my tour in Viet Nam. <br>
Jones had just lit a cigarette, reached over, and lit mine. As he stepped back and moved over to where John was kneeling, looking down the trail. I leaned back to enjoy the break from all the humping we had been doing since before daybreak. We had moved out early, first going south, away from the ville and roadway then I noticed that we had actually circled back around. <br>
As I took in a long drag I saw Jones who was by then standing to my right stiffen. His eyes widen and he ripped the cigarette he had been smoking from his mouth, throwing it to the ground. <br>
&quot;What a waste of a cigarette,&quot; I was thinking, when I saw that he raised his M16 rifle to his shoulder and open fire. <br>
John, who was sitting between us, hit the dirt, rolled on his stomach and immediately opened with a twenty round burst from his M16. Someone else to their left also opened up. As the rounds were exiting John's and Jones rifles I was already turning around and getting up behind the gun. <br>
Instinctively, I opened up full throttle. I had not seen anyone and was only shooting in the general direction that Jones and John were firing. I was scared, adrenaline was pumping me full of energy and whoever it was or what ever it was Jones and John were firing at, I wanted to fill full of lead and opened fired at the enemy whom I had not seen with a full blast of automatic machine gun fire.<br>
100 rounds of machinegun ammo goes fast and as soon as the first belt was expanded I slapped on another belt in a matter of seconds. Suddenly there was silence all around us. The area was filled with the smell of smoke, burning hot lead and gunpowder. The barrel of the gun was hot and smoke was freely flowing out of its front suppresser.  <br>
It was the first time I had opened fire in combat and all I can recall seeing while I was firing at an invisible enemy was the flash of the tracers, the noise, and fire power of the gun that seemed to have been responding with its own self will and determination. <br>
I found myself controlling the fire power toward the center of the targeted area, but only for the last forty rounds. It was then that I began to sweep the area just above ground level as I had been taught. It was at first, rare naked response to danger followed by disciplined military training. It was unlike any target practice. This time it was real and it was dangerous. I was expecting at any moment for rounds to come shooting back at us, but they never did. I realized that I had been determined to put a wall of lead out as quickly and accurately as possible, and felt that I had done all right.  When the dust settled the silence that followed was eerie. <br>
Later we recovered an NVA corpsman's medicine bag and some abandoned VC equipment. The medic bag had eight M60 machine gun bullets through it.  Whoever was wearing it or anyone near it had to be dead or at least badly wounded.We searched the area but found no more evidence of the enemy.  We were fighting an evasive and elusive enemy.  When we swept through the village, we knew that the villagers knew where the enemy had gone. The villagers who were mostly old men and women avoided eye contact by keeping their heads down and most of them stayed indoors.<br><br>
I realized that I had responded to Jones' firing, opened up without reservation and shot at the enemy in retaliation. I had shot at the enemy who killed Bro and Stroker, wounded Turner and McGinley and had taken US government issued military weapons. I realized I had opened fire for Bro and not for the South Vietnamese people.<br><br>
Funny thing, from then on, medals, honor, and praise from others for having done my job as a Marine no longer mattered. I never sought them after that.<br><br>
I have never forgotten my youthful days, the 4th of July was always special, and the whole town would come out to the park and share in the games and activities. We looked forward to it, much like Christmas. Christmas was family, the 4th of July was for the community. We all had pride in our country and in those that served in its services.<br><br>
What happened to AMERICA? What happened to what I fought for? What happened to our pride, honor and glory. What happened to justice and the American way? What happened to the 4th of July?<br><br>
Did we began to lose our pride, began to suffer survivor's guilt when this great nation abandon millions of Vietnamese to communist subversion and dominion. When we still had a weapon in our hands and a magazine full of ammo, they said cease firing. But they never did. <br><br>
